MYSTERIOUS SCROLL CRACKING/HACKING PUZZLE



Tom's 12-word recovery phrase and four secret words are the key to solving this puzzle. But can the puzzle be solved by someone other than Tom?

We suspected that the original bounty puzzle was only solvable by Dan, the guy who had the Skydrop treasure. In the end, the puzzle was solved by someone who was working with Dan and had his four secret words. But there was a lot of speculation, and the question remained: was it solvable without that information?

Obviously, Dan's 12-word recovery phrase had already been leaked, but there was even speculation about that: could the 21 messages be recovered simply via pattern analysis, without even knowing the 12 words? That is our first question here. I'm very curious about the answer.

The first person who emails jasonrohrer@fastmail.fm the 21 messages ALONG WITH a link to a YouTube video explaining how the messages were uncovered wins $500. The video can be unlisted when you email us, with the expectation that the winning video will be made public after the prize is awarded.

We strongly suspect that this first challenge is solvable, and that we'll be paying out this prize soon. But we'll all hopefully learn some interesting things along the way.

There is no Base-3 puzzle this time around. If you figure out the 21 messages, and know the Base-3 solution to the original bounty puzzle, you should have no trouble with the second table in the puzzle. That second table is included this time around to ensure that we have geographic ambiguity at exactly the same scales as we had it in the original bounty puzzle.

The third table, which uses Tom's secret words, is where things get really interesting. Of course, for the bounty, there was a lot of speculation about the possibility of brute-forcing Dan's words, and lots of scripts were hammering away at our server. Some of these scripts were literally attempted to try every combination out of 400 billion possibilities. Other scripts were shrinking the search space by considering only first and third words that landed in New England, and then trying all possibilities for the second and fourth words. That space is still in the billions, though. There are other ways to rule out even more words based on geography, but the space is still pretty large. The fastest scripts seemed to be making around 8 million attempts per day, and they didn't seem to start until around Sunday, October 14 or so. Thus, we're guessing that they hadn't cracked Dan's words by the night of Monday, October 15, when the bounty was found (through the use of Dan's words, directly from Dan).

Of course, there are loads more reasons why having scripts hit your server 8 million times a day is bad. So those hatches have been battened down. It's kindof amazing to us that the default installations of nginx and ufw and fail2ban just blindly go along, happily serving a hundred requests per second to the same IP address all day long. Even more surprising, there's no simple setting to thwart this. We eventually rolled our own solution, which manually detects and denies hammering IP addresses at the ufw (iptables) level. And of course, the Skydrop server code can watch out for IPs that are submitting incorrect 4-word guesses repeatedly, and stop those from continuing to guess much earlier.

Anyway, this is mostly a story about what people could have potentially figured out, rather than what they actually figured out. There is no evidence that anyone independently deduced Dan's secret words in time to retrieve the bounty.

The bounty was retrieved through Dan's cooperation, by someone who betrayed him.

But we're still curious about what is possible NOW: with a battened-down sever, but still with a medium-search-space security token that maps to real-world locations in exactly the same way they did in the initial bounty puzzle. Was the puzzle itself fundamentally crackable? Is our server fundamentally hackable?

But this time, tricking Dan is off the table. Tom's lips are sealed. The only way to crack this puzzle is to actually crack it, for real, or to hack our server in ways that we hope aren't possible.

As long as you don't commit physical crimes, all possible methods are fair game here, including social engineering, etc. If there are weak points, we want to know what they are. We're also curious about whether "brute forcing" physical space is possible. For example, if you somehow narrow it down to a 1 km x 1 km area, is it game over? That's a million square meters, don't forget. A million is not a lot when it comes to security tokens, but it's an awful lot of ground to walk across. Even walking the whole thing briskly, without really looking closely, would take 4 solid 24-hour days.

The first person to email jasonrohrer@fastmail.fm a photograph of the scroll that has been hidden in the woods, ALONG WITH a link to a YouTube video explaining how the scroll was found, wins $2000. The video can be unlisted when you email us, with the expectation that the winning video will be made public after the prize is awarded.

We strongly suspect that this second challenge is impossible, and that the jar will sit out there until the metal band rust through, the jar fills with water, and a tree sprouts from the humus that the mysterious scroll eventually becomes. Our bet is that our $2000 is safe, and that we will never need to pay out this prize.

But if we're wrong, we have a lot of amazing things to learn.



Good skill,
Jason and Tom
